<br>
In my mind the specific sections should be an archive, not a mandatory place to post topics. Have a look at Graffe's, a much busier board than here, and you'll see that there are topics on everything Wizardly in the main section. <br>
<br>
Topics that have been discussed at length and are fresh should be moved to section-specific areas rather than it being a requirement to post there.<br>
<br>
There are just not enough readers and especially not posters to the board to support the number of forums and the board remain productive and useful.<br>
<br>
There are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>thirty three forums here!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. There are twenty two people currently on the site, and you can bet that it would be a rare day (patch etc) that saw the number of readers eclipse the number of forums.<br>
<br>
Some questions:<br>
<br>
Why is the Epic Pet a seperate forum from the Quest? There's not <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>that much</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to know about either.<br>
<br>
I've said it before, but why are there forums for every single spell level's adventuring? <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>half the board's forums are here</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Condense to Apprentice, Journeyman, Master, and Convoker representing enough of the phases of life in the magician's career. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Levels 8-11</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> has been here as long as I have and has a whoopping 81 posts and doesn't even rate a second page of topics.<br>
<br>
I was simply annoyed to come back to some interesting discussions I had been following to see that they had all been stifled. <br>
<br>
Yes, we will rehash stuff. But I put it to you, that this is inevitable - there's just not that much about being as mage that you won't see repetition after a couple of years. Its an inherent evil in the nature of message boards.<br>
<br>
I have no objection whatsoever to ther mods locking threads that are simple questions that have been thoroughly discussed and an answer is found elsewhere, especially if the answer thread has been linked. But often, discussion twists away from the original question - we've all seen it! - and by stifling it you will drive people away. <p><center>
